text.paragraph:
Because of incompletely developed renal function in neonates and young infants, the elimination of amoxicillin may be delayed. Dosing of amoxicillin should be modified in pediatric patients 12 weeks or younger (3 months or younger) [see Dosage and Administration (
                           Error! Hyperlink reference not valid.
                           )].

Amoxicillin is primarily eliminated by the kidney and dosage adjustment is usually required in patients with severe renal impairment (GFR less than 30 mL/min). See Dosing in Renal Impairment (
                           Error! Hyperlink reference not valid.
                           ) for specific recommendations in patients with renal impairment.

Amoxicillin is an antibacterial drug [see Microbiology (
                           Error! Hyperlink reference not valid.
                           )].

Metabolism and Excretion: The half-life of amoxicillin is 61.3 minutes. Approximately 60% of an orally administered dose of amoxicillin is excreted in the urine within 6 to 8 hours. Detectable serum levels are observed up to 8 hours after an orally administered dose of amoxicillin. Since most of the amoxicillin is excreted unchanged in the urine, its excretion can be delayed by concurrent administration of probenecid [see Drug Interactions (
Error! Hyperlink reference not valid.
)].

Amoxicillin has been shown to be active against most isolates of the following microorganisms, both in vitro and in clinical infections [see Indications and Usage (
                           Error! Hyperlink reference not valid.
                           )].

Advise patients about the signs and symptoms of serious skin manifestations. Instruct patients to stop taking amoxicillin immediately and promptly report the first signs or symptoms of skin rash, mucosal lesions, or any other sign of hypersensitivity [see Warnings and Precautions (
                     Error! Hyperlink reference not valid.
                     )].
